1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3 {Maybe not such a bad move after all. White
threatens to occupy the centre with d2-d4, just "a bit" earlier than this
happens in the Ruy Lopez (if Black does not interfere with this sweet plan by
choosing the Open variation or the Marshall Attack, of course). And since
Carlsen does not seem to be too keen to sustain long theoretical discussions,
the Ponziani is the perfect one-game-opening.} ({It is interesting to compare
the game position after 7 moves with that arising after} 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d4 exd4
5. e5 d5 6. Bb5 Ne4 7. Nxd4 {Obviously, White has an extra tempo in the
Ponziani (c2-c3) with respect to an entirely approved opening! In the
two-knight defence, the main line goes} Bc5 {, to be cpmpared wth the similar
line below.}) 3... Nf6 4. d4 d5 5. Bb5 exd4 (5... Nxe4 6. Nxe5 Bd7 7. Nxd7 (7.
Qb3 {1-0 Prokopchuk,E-Sofieva,A (2385)/St Petersburg 1994/CBM 041/[Hecht] (74)}
) 7... Qxd7 8. O-O Be7 9. Nd2 Nxd2 10. Bxd2 a6 (10... O-O 11. Qf3 a6 12. Ba4
Rfe8 13. Rae1 Bf8 14. h4 Rad8 15. Bc2 Ne7 16. h5 c6 17. Bxh7+ Kxh7 18. Qxf7 Qg4
19. Re6 Nf5 20. f3 Nxd4 21. Rh6# {1-0 (21) Delgado Ramirez,N (2609)-Heinechen,
J (1965) Asuncion PAR 2015}) 11. Bd3 O-O 12. Qf3 $14 {Estrin,Y-Vasilchuk,Y/
Moscow 1961/MCD (1-0, 42)}) 6. e5 Ne4 7. Nxd4 (7. cxd4 Bb4+ 8. Nbd2 O-O 9. O-O
Bxd2 10. Bxd2 Nxd2 11. Qxd2 Ne7 12. Rac1 c6 13. Bd3 Ng6 $17) 7... Bd7 {This
looks a bit passive.} ({I have the feeling that} 7... Bc5 {may be the critical
continuation anyway, even with the extra c2-c3. After all, Black does not
necessarily want to put pressure on d4, but rather weaken the presure over c6
and for this reason c2-c3 is not too relevant.} 8. O-O (8. Nxc6 Bxf2+ (8...
Nxf2 9. Kf1 bxc6 10. Bxc6+ Kf8 11. Bxa8 Ba6+ $19) 9. Kf1 bxc6 10. Bxc6+ Kf8 $13
{Kastell,M-Jonasson,P SVE-ch Klass corr 1999 (1-0, 23)}) (8. Nd2 $5) 8... O-O
9. f3 (9. Bxc6 bxc6 10. Be3 (10. b4 Bb6 11. Be3 (11. Nxc6 Qe8 12. Qxd5 Nxf2)
11... Qe8 12. f3 Nd6 13. Bf4 Nc4 14. Re1 c5 15. bxc5 Bxc5 16. Nd2 Nxd2 17. Qxd2
Qa4 18. Kh1 Qc4 19. Rad1 Be6 20. Bg5 Rfe8 21. f4 Bg4 22. Rb1 h6 23. Bh4 Rab8
24. h3 Bd7 25. Rb3 Rb6 26. Bf2 Bf8 (26... Ba4) 27. f5 c5 28. e6 $1 fxe6 29.
Nxe6 Bxe6 30. Rxb6 axb6 31. fxe6 Be7 32. Qb2 Bd8 33. Bg3 $1 b5 34. Qc2 Bf6 35.
Qg6 Re7 36. Bd6 $1 Qxc3 37. Re2 Qc4 38. Qh5 Ra7 39. e7 Bxe7 40. Bxe7 Qc1+ 41.
Kh2 Qf4+ 42. Kg1 Qd4+ 43. Kh2 Qf4+ 44. g3 Qc4 $1 45. Bf6 Rxa2 46. Bb2 Qd3 47.
Rf2 Ra7 48. Qe5 Kh7 49. h4 b4 50. Rf8 Qe4 51. Qb8 Ra2 $1 52. Rf2 Qb1 53. Qe5 d4
54. Kh3 Rxb2 {1/2-1/2 (54) Shannon,P-Owen,L USA-ch7 corr8790 1987}) (10. f3 f6
11. fxe4 fxe5 12. Rxf8+ Qxf8 13. Be3 exd4 14. cxd4) (10. Nxc6 $2 Qh4 11. Be3
Ba6 12. Re1 Nxf2 $19) 10... Qe8 {'!'} (10... Bd7 $2 11. Nd2 Nxd2 12. Qxd2 Qe7
13. Rae1 Bb6 14. b4 a5 15. Bg5 Qe8 16. Bf6 $14) 11. f3 (11. Nd2 Bd7) 11... Nd6
$15 {Gligoric,S-Keller,D Zuerich 1959 MCL [Bulletin] (1-0, 38) '!'} 12. Bf2 Nc4
13. b4 Bb6 14. Re1 c5 $15) (9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Bxc6 Ba6 {'-+'} 11. Nd2 Bxf1 12.
Nxe4 dxe4 13. Qxf1 Rb8 {Onderdelinden,D-Rosenhahn,E ICCF-Cup corr 1994 (0-1,
34)}) 9... Ng5 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. Be3 f6 {Gligoric,S-Fischer,R Buenos Aires
1960 (1/2, 20). Well, if Fischer, on a very rare occasion when he deviated
from his 1...c5, chose this line, there may be something behind it.
Unfortunately, it is impossible to put these two great players, Fischer and
Carlsen, who reached unthinkable rating peaks of their time, to rehearse this
position against eachother...}) 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. O-O Be7 10. Be3 {This looks
logical,} ({but} 10. f3 Nc5 11. f4 {does not seem too bad either:} O-O (11...
f5 $2 12. b4 Ne4 13. e6 $16 {Schneider,L (2410)-Moen,O (2315)/Eksjo 1981/MCL 
(1-0, 29)}) 12. Be3 $6 (12. f5 $1 {is the critical line, leaving Black with
the permanent threats of e5-e6 and f5-f6.}) 12... f6 $132 {Panchev,P (2365)
-Schoene,R (2360) Karl-Marx-Stadt 1990 (0-1, 42)}) 10... O-O 11. Nd2 Nc5 (11...
Nxd2 12. Qxd2 c5 13. Ne2 ({It makes more sense to fight for the c5-square:} 13.
Nb3 c4 14. Nc5 Bf5 15. b3 $14) 13... Bb5 14. Rfd1 Bxe2 15. Qxe2 Qd7 $11 {
Dueckstein,A-Unzicker,W/Siegen 1970/EXT 2002 (1/2, 29)}) 12. b4 $146 (12. f4 $5
f5 $6 (12... a5 $6 13. f5 Nd3 14. f6 $40) (12... f6 $1 13. b4 $6 fxe5 $1) 13.
b4 Ne6 $6 (13... Ne4 $14) 14. N2b3 $16 {Basman,M-Masters,D/Bath 1963/EXT 1999 
(1-0, 31)}) 12... Nb7 $6 {Too passive, I believe.} ({The provocative} 12... Nd3
$5 {may offer better chances for counterplay.} 13. f4 (13. N2f3 Nb2 14. Qc2 Nc4
) 13... a5 (13... c5 14. bxc5 Nxc5 15. Qf3 $36) 14. Qc2 (14. a3 axb4 15. axb4
Rxa1 16. Qxa1 c5 $132) 14... axb4 15. Qxd3 c5 $44) 13. f4 a5 14. f5 $5 {
This promising pawn sacrifice would not have been possible with the black
knight on d3 rather than b7.} axb4 15. cxb4 Bxb4 16. Qg4 {White's compensation
consists of two elements: his kingside threats and the idea of blocking the
enemy queenside pawns on c5 and d4.} Bc3 (16... c5 $2 17. Bh6 g6 18. Nc6 $1
Bxc6 19. fxg6 hxg6 20. Rxf7 $1 $18) 17. Rac1 Bxd4 18. Bxd4 Rxa2 {It is not
easy to find a good moment to fight against the blockade with ...c6-c5. This
is a result of the combined threats on both wings, quite an effective method
of play.} (18... c5 19. e6 cxd4 20. f6 g6 21. exd7 $16) 19. e6 f6 20. Nb3 {
Now and later, Carlsen will constantly choose the static approach, refraining
from turning the game dynamic. It is not easy to judge whether he was right,
maybe sometimes he was and other times not, but the course of the game is
suggestive for his general style.} (20. Rce1 $5 Rxd2 21. e7 Qe8 22. exf8=Q+
Qxf8 23. Qf4 Rd3 24. Qxc7 $36) 20... Be8 21. Nc5 Nd6 22. Qf3 Qe7 ({I would not
resist playing} 22... Nb5 {, with constant pressure against d4. In this case,
White would have enjoyed lesser freedom to build up his attack, although play
would have remained slightly one-sided anyway.}) 23. Rf2 Ra5 24. Nb3 Rb5 25.
Bc5 Bh5 26. Qc3 {White has achieved a faourable regrouping and can count on an
advantage.} Qe8 27. Qe3 (27. Nd4 $16) 27... Qa8 (27... Ne4 28. Bxf8 Nxf2 29.
Nd4 Ng4 30. Qg3 Qxf8 31. Nxb5 cxb5 32. Qxc7 $18) 28. Nd4 Rxc5 29. Rxc5 Ne4 30.
Nxc6 Nxf2 31. Kxf2 Qa2+ 32. Kg3 Re8 33. h3 $16 {The position has calmed down,
White has exchanged all the superfluous pieces and can enjoy his blockade.
Black can only sit and wait to be crushed.} Qa6 34. Qc3 Be2 35. Rxd5 Bb5 36.
Nb4 Qb7 37. Qc5 Ba4 38. Rd7 Qe4 39. Rxc7 h5 40. Kh2 Kh7 41. Qf2 Rg8 42. Na6 Be8
43. Rc5 Qd3 44. Nb4 Qd6+ 45. Kh1 Qd1+ 46. Qg1 Qd6 47. Nd5 Rf8 48. Qd4 Kh8 49.
Rc8 Bc6 1-0

